{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f95ae10f-92d3-4875-8e43-893783df1fc5","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. Look here:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   ```\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\nFor a **core dump** (for use with `lldb`), you need to opt in:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nThen re-run your app. Core files land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You may also need to disable SIP or grant Full Disk Access depending on your macOS version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7554135a-dbcd-43d5-84f8-5a81a2409b80","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":259},"id":"304869fe-e4aa-4b6e-921f-fe4502eb3a75","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:00:59.740Z","parentId":"930079d1-0621-4d81-a315-ec88e94698c7"}
